article.headline: Blue Devils win by 34, but coach despises turnovers

article.linkText: No. 1 Duke continues to keep Saint Joseph's in the dark
article.story:
DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- Saint Joseph's spent a night without
electricity after an ice storm hit the Raleigh-Durham area and then
watched No. 1 Duke shoot the lights out in an 82-48 victory Sunday in
the championship game of the Duke Women's Basketball Classic.

<photo1>

	   Duke (7-0) led throughout, but coach Gail Goestenkors roasted
her players afterward for their 21 turnovers.

	   ''I was not really impressed with how we played. Twenty-one
turnovers is just not acceptable,'' she said. ''I was very upset
with our team.''

	   Alana Beard, the tournament most valuable player, scored 19 of her season-high 29
points in the second half to help Duke pull away from a 36-22
halftime lead.

	   She had nine rebounds to help Duke dominate the boards, 39-20.
Mistie Bass added 16 points and Sheana Mosch had 10 for Duke.

	   ''We wore them down a bit in the second half and our bench was a
factor in that,'' Goestenkors said. ''That's one of our real
strengths -- depth, and quality depth.''

	   Stephanie Graff and Amra Mehmedic each scored 11 points for
Saint Joseph's (2-3).

	   Duke shot 56.1 percent from the field (32-for-57), while limiting
Saint Joseph's to 39.2 percent shooting.

	   ''You can tell a team 'We can play with these guys,' but until
they execute and hit the open shots they get, they won't believe
it,'' Saint Joseph's coach Cindy Griffin said.

	   Griffin blamed the poor shooting partly on intimidation by Duke.

	   ''If any year is the year to win it all, this is the year for
Duke. This is Duke's year,'' she said. ''They've been really good
for four, five years, and now they seem to have all the answers
they didn't have before.''

	   Saint Joseph's might have expected trouble after rolling into
Durham on Friday, shortly after a major ice storm knocked out power
to more about one million customers, Griffin said.

	   ''We had power at our hotel when we checked in and then the
lights went out,'' she said. ''It really kept us off balance.
Between that and this game, this is one trip we won't forget
anytime soon.''

	   Iciss Tillis, who had 22 points and 10 rebounds for Duke in its
128-53 first-round victory over Howard, joined Beard on the
all-tournament team along with Asia Petty of Howard, Buffalo's Kate
McMeeken-Ruscoe and Irina Krasnoshiok of Saint Joseph's.
